If you want that, you should make all your constructors `private` (so nobody but you can call them) and then create a `public static` method that allows you to build the object, which performs the checks before calling the constructors. Basically: 

    private Box() {
        //standard code
    }

    private Box(double depth) {
        //standard code
    }

    public static Box create(/*parameters*/) {
        //check parameters first
        //if all good call constructor, else throw
    }

However, just to make it clear to you, you&#39;re not going to save any computing time by throwing before or inside the constructor. 
It&#39;s rather a matter of code style than optimization.

For completeness sake, you can use validation method returning the input, if the validation passes:
```
private static double validate(double value) {
  if (value &lt;= 0) {
    throw new IllegalArgumentException(&quot;message&quot;);
  }
  return value;
}
```
And use it like this:
```
Box(double depth) {
  this(validate(depth), 40);
}
```
Inspired by [`Objects.requireNonNull()`][1].

Just to be explicit, I doubt the gains would be substantial enough to make it worth it, unless you want to adopt such code style for the project. TBH [Mateo&#39;s approach][2] with static factory method is cleaner.

